This Sir Peter Legh seems to have been at great pains to obtain a general pardon3 and several letters patent express] y pardoning him for all offences, general and particular, are in the custody of his descendants. The necessity for these letters of pardon might be different in those troublcsome times, when the law was not so clear, and men's lives were not so safe3 but our best antiquaries are of opinion that a pardon was never sought for, or granted, unless there had existed some cause of suspicion or offence.— Tyler's Henry quonmouth, p. 243.
